1. Dramatic decline in job satisfaction

The data

The cities-job-satisfaction.csv dataset contains (fictional) data from different cities around the world. In this data it was measured which proportion of people reported that they were unsatisfied with their work situation this year compared to last year. Each data point is a different city, and the value indicates the proportion of dissatisfied workers.

My plots

Altair

ggplot

My claim

You can clearly see in this plot that people are dramatically more dissatisfied at work this year compared to last year. I have used transparency for the dots to prevent overplotting/oversaturation, so this means that the entire dark area has an even amount of cities throughout. In other words, there are as many cities that increased from ~0% to ~40% dissatisfaction as there are cities that stayed around 0%. That's atrocious!

Question 1.1

rubric={reasoning:2,writing:1}

  • Explain which mistakes (if any) I have done in my plot and provide an interpretation of the data that is more correct than mine. Be brief and clear in your answer.
  • You might have some ideas just from looking at my plot, but you will likely need to do some investigation yourself to answer this question fully. You can reference your improved plot as needed.

The x and y scale are not the same so it makes interpretation difficult. The job satisfaction this year is on a scale from 0 to 0.8, and the scale for last year is from 0 to 1.7. Also the use of the word dissatisfaction is confusing. Ths plot is of job satisfaction, so we should say there was a decrese in job satisfaction from last year to this year. We could also create a box plot to better compare the distributions.

From my updated plot, we can see that there is trend line that has a slope of m < 1, therefore overall we have a overall decrease in job satisfaction from last year to this year.

2. I will keep raising wages for all

The data

The wages.csv dataset contains (fictional) data from different companies in the city where I have been the mayor for the last few years. Each datapoint represents the average salary at a company. All the major companies in this city were surveyed both before I was elected and after a few years of my governing. However, this is not paired data, some companies are different from "before" and "after", so you do not need to do a paired analysis.

My plots

Altair

ggplot

My claim

As you can see, I have been able to produce a significant increase in the average salary for workers in my city. This high raise almost certainly entails that all (or almost all) workers are receiving a higher payment than what they were before I started to govern. But since I know you are going to ask me for more robust estimates, I have also provided the median increase (which is even more notable) and the number of workers in each group (so that you can see that the samples are balanced).

alt.Chart(wages).transform_density(
    'salary',
    as_=['salary', 'density'],
    groupby=['when']
).mark_area(
).encode(
    x=alt.X('salary:Q'),
    y=alt.Y('density:Q'),
    color='when'
).facet(
    column=alt.Column('when:N',sort=['before','after'])
)
Out[8]:

YOUR ANSWER HERE

The main mistake in the original interpretation is the assumption that an increase in the mean and median salary implies that all, or almost all, workers received higher pay. Mean and median are measures of central tendency and only describe how the overall distribution shifts. They do not provide information about individual-level changes.

As shown in the reference density plot, the wage distributions before and after the policy change overlap substantially. This overlap indicates that some workers in the after group may earn less than workers in the upper part of the before distribution, and therefore did not necessarily experience a wage increase.

# YOUR ANSWER HERE
density = alt.Chart(wages).transform_density(
    'salary',
    as_=['salary', 'density'],
    groupby=['when']
).mark_area(opacity=0.6).encode(
    x=alt.X('salary:Q', title='Salary'),
    y=alt.Y('density:Q', title='Density'),
    color=alt.Color('when:N', legend=None)
)

mean_line = alt.Chart(wages).transform_aggregate(
    mean_salary='mean(salary)',
    groupby=['when']
).transform_calculate(
    stat='"Mean"'
).mark_rule(strokeDash=[4,2], size=2).encode(
    x='mean_salary:Q',
    color=alt.Color('when:N', legend=None),
    strokeDash=alt.StrokeDash(
        'stat:N',
        legend=alt.Legend(title='Statistic')
    )
)

median_line = alt.Chart(wages).transform_aggregate(
    median_salary='median(salary)',
    groupby=['when']
).transform_calculate(
    stat='"Median"'
).mark_rule(size=2).encode(
    x='median_salary:Q',
    color=alt.Color('when:N', legend=None),
    strokeDash=alt.StrokeDash(
        'stat:N',
        legend=alt.Legend(title='Statistic')
    )
)

alt.layer(density, mean_line, median_line).facet(
    column=alt.Column('when:N', sort=['before', 'after'], title=None)
).properties(title=alt.TitleParams(text='Density Plot for Before and After Salaries',anchor='middle'))

Improve my ggplot plot. Chose the best type of plot to accurately reveal what the data looks like. Design the plot to be an effective plot for communication purposes, this includes proper figure size, axis/figure titles, font sizes, colors, etc. You can either make a single or several plots, depending on what you think is needed.

In[17]:
%%R -h 300 -w 600
# YOUR ANSWER HERE

wages <- wages %>% mutate(when = factor(when, levels = c("before", "after")))

line_df <- wages %>%
  group_by(when) %>%
  summarise(
    mean = mean(salary),
    median = median(salary),
    .groups = "drop"
  ) %>%
  tidyr::pivot_longer(
    cols = c(mean, median),
    names_to = "stat",
    values_to = "value"
  )

ggplot(wages, aes(x = salary, colour = when, fill = when)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.6) +

  geom_vline(
    data = line_df,
    aes(xintercept = value, linetype = stat),
    linewidth = 1
  ) +

  facet_wrap(~ when, nrow = 1) +

  scale_linetype_manual(
    values = c(mean = "dashed", median = "solid"),
    name = "Statistic"
  ) +

  labs(
    x = "Salary",
    y = "Density",
    title = "Density Plot for Before and After Salary",
    subtitle = "Dashed lines indicate mean; solid lines indicate median"
  ) +

  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, face = "bold"),
    legend.position = "right",
    legend.key.width=unit(1,'cm')
  )

%%R
library(ggplot2)

guns = read.csv("guns-r-us.csv")

chart = ggplot(guns, aes(x = Year, y = Firearm.murders)) +
  geom_area(fill = "red") +
  geom_line(color = "black", linewidth = 1) +
  geom_point(fill = "black", color = "black", size = 2) +
  annotate("text", x = 2005, y = 200, label = "Gun law enacted",
           color = "white", fontface = "bold", hjust = 0) +
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Year",
                     breaks = c(1990, 1995, 2000, 2005, 2010, 2015),
                     limits = c(1990, 2015),
                     expand = expansion(mult = c(0, 0.03))) +
  scale_y_reverse(name = "Firearm murders",
                  limits = c(900, 0),
                  breaks = c(250, 500, 750)) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    panel.grid.major.x = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor.x = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor.y = element_line(color = "lightgrey", linewidth = 0.5),
    panel.border = element_rect(color = "black", linewidth = 1),
    axis.title.x = element_text(size = 20),
    axis.title.y = element_text(size = 20),
    axis.text.x = element_text(size = 14),
    axis.text.y = element_text(size = 14)
  )

The data

The (fictional) state-comparison.csv dataset contains a sample of voters from my state and a neighboring state of similar socioeconomic standard. Voters in each state were asked to rate their approval of the state's mayor on a scale from 0 - 10,000.

My claim

My approval ratings are through the roof! I am clearly doing a better job than my colleague and competitor next doors. And as you can see we sampled enough people to get smooth curves, which means that this difference is both likely to be statistically significant and the magnitude is just too big to ignore. There seems to be a few bores on the lower end of the spectrum, but can't win them all I guess. Do you want a 10k approval rating future? Vote Ostblom in 2020!

YOUR ANSWER HERE

Although the original data may have been sampled from a large number of individuals, it has already been aggregated at the state level. As a result, each group contains only three observations, which is far too small to support a meaningful density plot. Kernel density estimation assumes a sufficiently large sample size to approximate an underlying continuous distribution, an assumption that is clearly violated here.

In addition, the dataset does not include any time dimension. Therefore, the density plot cannot be interpreted as representing future approval rates or trends. Instead, it merely reflects the distribution of a small number of aggregated values at a single point in time, making the density visualization potentially misleading.

library(scales)

state=read.csv('state-comparison.csv')
ggplot(state, aes(x = `the.value`, fill = where, colour = where)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.6) +
  scale_x_continuous(
    limits = c(0, 10000),
    breaks = seq(0, 10000, by = 2000),
    labels = function(x) {ifelse(x != 0, paste0(x / 1000, "k"), "0")}
  ) + 
  scale_y_continuous(
    limits = c(0e+00, 1.1e-04),
    breaks = seq(0e+00, 1.0e-04, by = 1.0e-04/4),
  ) +
  scale_fill_manual(
    values = c("My state" = "#4C78A8", "Neighboring states" = "#72B7B2")
  ) +
  scale_colour_manual(
    values = c("My state" = "#4C78A8", "Neighboring states" = "#72B7B2")
  ) +
  labs(
    x = "the value",
    y = "density",
    title = "Ocean Waves"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    legend.title = element_blank(),

# YOUR ANSWER HERE
bars = (
    alt.Chart(state)
    .transform_aggregate(
        mean_value='mean(the value)',
        groupby=['where']
    )
    .mark_bar(opacity=0.6,width=50)
    .encode(
        x=alt.X('where:N', title='Where',axis=alt.Axis(labelAngle=0)), #changing label angle
        y=alt.Y('mean_value:Q', title='Average Approval Rate'),
        fill=alt.Fill(
            'where:N',
            scale=alt.Scale(domain=['My state', 'Neighboring states'],
                            range=['#1f78b4', '#33a02c']),
        legend=alt.Legend(orient='top') # adding legend
        ),
        tooltip=[
            alt.Tooltip('where:N', title='Group'),
            alt.Tooltip('mean_value:Q', title='Mean approval rate', format='.2f')
        ]
    )
)

labels = (
    alt.Chart(state)
    .transform_aggregate(
        mean_value='mean(the value)',
        groupby=['where']
    )
    .mark_text(dy=-8)
    .encode(
        x='where:N',
        y='mean_value:Q',
        text=alt.Text('mean_value:Q', format='.2f')
    )
)

points = (
    alt.Chart(state)
    .mark_point(size=80)
    .encode(
        x='where:N',
        y='the value:Q',
        color=alt.Color(
            'where:N',
            scale=alt.Scale(domain=['My state', 'Neighboring states'],
                            range=['#08306b', '#00441b']),
        )
    )
)

(bars + points+ labels).properties(
    width=300,
    height=400,
    title='Approval Rate Comparison' #adding title
)
Out[30]:

Several communication-related improvements were applied to the original chart to make it clearer and easier to interpret:

  1. Axis label orientation The x-axis labels were rotated to a horizontal orientation to improve readability and prevent awkward vertical text, especially for longer category names.

  2. Legend addition A legend was added to clearly distinguish between the two states, allowing viewers to easily associate colors with their corresponding groups.

  3. Title enhancement A descriptive title was added to provide context and clearly communicate the purpose of the visualization at a glance.

  4. Value labels on bars Numeric labels showing the average approval rate were placed above each bar, enabling precise value comparison without requiring the reader to estimate values from the axis.

  5. New parameter not discussed in lecture: Tooltip An interactive tooltip was added to display exact values when hovering over bars or points. This feature improves communication by providing detailed information on demand while keeping the visual display clean and uncluttered.
